The rivers were here long before civilization came and they dont recognize any political country borders. Kind of the same do kayakers with spirit of freedom and free flow. From a kayakers point of view Northern Portugal and Spanish province of Galicia is one big whitewater area. It doesnt make any sense to separate them as many rivers run through both countries and even if they are not they still have the same character, style and season.

**Culture and security**

With minor exceptions the borders of Portugal stay unchanged since 1249. In some researches modern Portugal is recognised as the third peaceful country in the world.

Yes its very peaceful and hostile! You can feel it even if you dont know it especially in remote mountain areas on the North of the country. Most of the locals you will interact with will appear incredibly hostile and generous people.

There are some exceptions like big city centers and beaches. These places attract pickpockets and other kinds of criminals. Some beaches are really full of them and its not safe to leave a car with belongings inside at these kind of places.

While travelling between the rivers in both Galicia and Portugal you dont have to worry about your car or belongings inside. However dont leave anything unlocked or outside of your car. An unlocked bicycle at a take out might be stolen along with your drybag with dry clothes. Hide it.

**Camping**

In Galicia and especially in Northern Portugal its generally OK to sleep in a car or even to wild camp.Usually its not easy to find a place where camping is legal in free. There are some designed places for overnight stays in camper vans in both countries. Normally locals dont mind if you stay in rural places and respect common rules of environmental friendly camping.

Northern Portugal has less uninhabited places than Galicia and in some valleys its not easy to find a place to camp or even to sleep in a car. On the other side its less likely to get strong objections from locals in Portugal.

Most of the campsites are closed during winter seasons in the area. Apartments and houses for rent are really cheap

**Roads and driving**

The mountains of Galicia and Portugal are covered with a pretty good quality road network. There is almost no snow here so most of the local roads follow mountain crests really high and far from river beds. Most of the runs in the area are pretty remote in deep gorges far from roads. Quite often it takes a lot of time to shuttle because you need to drive up to a mountain top from a put in and then go even more down to a take out.

Even small local roads are very high quality in Spain. In Portugal the quality is much worse so be patient Although Portuguese people are famous for being relaxed and patient its often not the case on the roads. There are no tunnels and high bridges on local roads so driving these narrow roads with endless bends takes a lot of time. The average speed of 40 km/h is normal here. There are numerous highways both in Portugal and Spain. In Portugal you have to pay for any stretch of a highway but there are 2 different systems of tolls. Be sure to deal with automatic tolls in Portugal before you have arrived to the country. In Galicia there are both toll and free highways. All tolls are manual for tourists. Google maps work perfect to navigate here and to choose between free and toll roads.

**Kayaking style**

Galicia and Portugal is a granite paradise. There are quite a lot of different styles of kayaking here. Despite many prejudices there is some big-volume kayaking and its not only class II-III. Just check out Tamega, Paiva, Deza few days after a rainfall. Most of the other rivers are creeks of any sizes. A typical river is a creek of 10 cumecs with some really clean pool-drop bedrock sections with slides and waterfalls interrupted suddenly by boulder gardens. These boulder gardens vary from smooth and technical to some really nasty and chaotic ones. There are very few demanding canyons with must-runs. Most of the sections are easy to scout and to portage. There are almost no landslides since the rock is quite solid. Many boulder garden sections are even safer with medium-high water levels because low flows uncover syphons.

**Water Levels**

Rains is the source of around 90% of water in the rivers. There are just few runnable rivers here that get some snow melt water occasionally (Castro Laboreiro, Peneda, Cabreira, Azere). There are more early snow melt rivers on the East of Galicia and further East in Asturias. So basically there is water in the region when it rains. The rains normally start in late autumn and stop in spring. But the tricky point is that different rivers have different speed of drying. At least half of the rivers are in narrow gorges all the way and they drain really fast. Rivers like Vez (with tributaries), Olo, Upper Tea, Cabril, Cavez can be runnable only 6-20 hours after a heavy rain although they can be too high when it''s raining really hard. In 2 days they will be dry no matter how hard was the rain.

At the same time there are rivers with a big flat basin and they can stay with a normal runnable flow for weeks! These rivers are usually bigger and much more famous because they have water way more often. But it doesn''t mean they are better quality than others! So if you a lucky with rain the suggestion is to postpone paddling classics and try to catch good flows in less popular creeks. Castro Laboreiro, Paiva, Tamega, Louredo, Oitaven, Deza stay with water for more than a week. Beca, Cavado, Tea, Varosa have water around 1 week after rain. Most of these rivers are also too high for few days after a heavy rain. Castro Laboreiro and Oitaven are too high for more than a week.

_It''s important - all rivers flood really fast if it rains hard!_

If there is no water at all in the region there are still couple options left. You can have a fun section at the easy section of Mio river (Arbo-Melgaco). Although it''s only grade II-III there is some stuff to play around and it always has water. Check out the wind/surf forecast and go to the beach! You might catch really nice ocean waves.

The other idea is to check out the forecast and current conditions in Central Spain, Asturias and Cantabria. There might be some occasional snow melt or some local rain in Cantabria coming from the North.

In Galicia there are very precised and frequently updated online gauges. We provide the readings of these gauges in the Whitewater.guide app upon an agreement with Galician government.

In Portugal there are also a lot of gauges but the real time data from them is not available for public.

**Other Guidebooks**

Before the whitewater.guide app people used to use several sources for the region. Portugal is covered by Rui Calado in the book called "Portugal kayak". The online version is available for purchase [here](about:blank). This guidebook is not only in Portuguese but also in English! The simple version of this guidebook is available for free [here](about:blank). It covers a lot of runs but there are also some nice ones that are not covered (Cabreiro, zere, Upper Upper Louredo, Cabril, Cavez). Rui was very kind to allow us to use the information from his guidebook in the Whitewater.guide app.

Northern and Eastern Galicia is covered in a high quality modern paper guidebook "Al Sur del Pirineo" by Fernando Alonso and Mario Calvo but it''s only in Spanish. The book can be purchased [here](about:blank). The authors also allowed us to use the information in our app.

A lot of Galician rivers and some Portuguese rivers are covered in a very old guidebook by Andres Sio Gonzalez (1996). Maybe it''s available [here](https://www.canotier.com/fr/kayak-en-galicia). The guidebook is in French and Spanish. It''s not really relevant because of new dams and roads were built but it covers some not famous rivers with no other info on them (Arnoia, Almofrei etc.)

The local paddler Alejandro Ochoa has [the blog](the bloghttp://kayakgalicia.blogspot.it/p/guia-de-kayak.html) with some interesting descriptions in Spanish and Galician and coordinates of some unknown rivers.

