**Water**

The Samana can be paddled at any flow. During floods it becomes an impressive big-big-huge-volume run! In dry season it''s a beautifl river with transparent water and nice rapids.

Most likely the river will suffer from the dam construction soon.

**The run**

You will get your wake up call just at the put in - there are few very nice and pushy class III+ rapids. There is a lot of flat water after that. The whole section is in a spectacular steep gorge full of tropical vegetation on the river banks. Pure jungle adventure!

There are around 3 solid class IV rapids on this section. Some of them definitely require scouting. When you see the big Guatape river trapped into pipes rushing into Samana from the left - it''s time to get out if you don''t want to paddle the following class IV-V gorge.

**Access**

The _put in_ is at the main highway bridge over Samana.

The usual _take out_ is the bridge called "Narices". If you are ok with class V just go down and paddle the [short canyon](http://wwater.tk/sections/uX7So2repSb84mRwD). This canyon just after the confluence with Guatape river is significantly harder and you can take out just at the confluence if you don''t want to paddle it. Actually it''s not a normal confluence it''s a huge artificial water release into Samana. There is a road going to that place but it''s locked. Try to ask someone to open it for you.

The shuttle from the put in to the take out takes around 5 hours and the road to the take out might be really bad after rains and hardly doable with a normal car.

**Note:** This section is at really low altitude. Beware of mosquito bites!!

_Mike Krutyansky, 2016_

