The Veo river could be one of the famous Norwegian highlights if there was no dam. Veo is fed by snow and glaciers but usually there is not enough water to paddle it even in the high season. There is no online gauge on Veo so the best advice would be just drive over the take out bridge and see if the dam releases enough water. [This is](/public/eL7XPhB2W6dsYwSJf.jpg) how it looks from the bridge when it''s low but already good for paddling. It might happen when the area is really high and the [gauge](/gauges/972seu2xBAKdLZpnZ) downstream at Sjoa river shows around 150 cumecs,

**Access**

The gorge you are going to paddle is really remote and there is even no road in the Veo valley all the way up to put in. When you drive up park as soon as you can see the river from the car and just carry your boats to the river downhill. Shallow flat water upstream is really not nice to paddle!

**The run**

Plan plenty of time. You will start from very anoying class II with very sharp rocks. It might feel too low but no worries you will enter the gorge soon. The rapids will become steeper and steeper and the river will narrow. With a lot of water this sharp boulder garden part in the canyon is the most demanding.

Then the river will change the style to bedrock. This part starts from an easy portage of a short and low canyon. Some parts of this portage can be paddled at certain flows. Here you will find a foot bridge. After that the bedrock fun starts - not that easy and fair! At this part you will be happy to have a low flow.

The bedrock fun comes to the end at some point and you start paddling continious class III-IV. Be carefull at the take out! You can scout the last paddleable and unpaddleable drops from the bridge of the main road and another bridge just a bit upstream.

Note: This valley has all the mosquitoes of Norway!

_Mike Krutyansky, 2015_', 'Heavy warm rains', 'It''s hard to find water in the river because of a dam', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.194979+00', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.194979+00');

This section of San Juan is a dream for any class IV kayaker. Endless fair rapids that don''t really require scouting but already are steep enough to practice boofing every 10-20 meters! They might change a bit but in 2016 there was only one landslide rapid slightly above grade IV just at the end of the section.

Some sections are really long and continuous.

The further you paddle the steeper the banks are and actually you enter the canyon even before the take out. But no worries it''s really hard to miss the take out bridge which is also the put in for the [canyon section](/sections/ojkThMJXLpJ5GqZcP/).

_Mike Krutyansky, 2017_

