**About the river**

Rio Cabreiro is in the shade of its brothers like upper Vez and Azere and it has probably been paddled only twice to this moment. And it''s unfair for such a pure gem of Portuguese whitewater rivers. This run is much better than Azere and the same good as upper Vez but longer and a bit less steep.

**Water**

The river rises and drops fast so be ready that the water level can change while you are paddling. Don''t put in if it''s raining hard even if the level seems low.

The good flow is 4-8 cumecs. Most likely 10-12 cumecs is also good for all sections except the tripple drop combo.

The river is good 1-2 days after a heavy rainfall or during the periods of moderate-light rains. Usually it''s the same time when upper Vez and Azere are also good.

**The run**

Everything is possible to scout but there are couple class IV must-runs. There is only one potentialy hard portage of the tripple drop in a canyon but at normal water level it''s runnable with no problem. Plan the whole day for this trip. You can also start from the alternative put in 1 km downstream but you will miss some nice whitewater then.

The run starts with easy read and run rapids class III-IV.

Soon you reach the first class V rapid - it''s a steep S-bend with a dangerous towback at the end. No shame to portage or to set up a proper safety here.

After few other rapids you enter the first canyon. It''s not easy to scout some parts of it but it''s all runnable and the lines are not hard.

The rapids become cleaner and more fun and even a small portage on the left (or a chicken line at higher flows) of a big unnranable drop doesn''t spoil the fun.

After some nice rapids ypu finally reach the waterfall combo in a super narrow canyon. It looks like narrow gates to nowhere from the river level and it''s impossible to miss. Scout and portage if necessary on the right.

After the waterfalls and all the way to the take there are numerous class IV-V- clean and not so clean drops that are all easy to scout and to portage.

_Note:_ There must be some steep stuff upstream the put in.

_Mike Krutyansky, 2017_', 'After rain', '1-2 days after a heavy rainfall or during the periods of moderate-light rains. 5-15 cumecs', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.258365+00', '2018-03-24 15:12:49.258365+00');

**Water**

Usually this section is paddled at low flows. The normal level is 2-4 cumecs which usually happens 3-7 days after a heavy rainfall. But Cavado can also be paddled with much more water. The overall grade will become something like class V.

**The run**

This description is based on "low" water which is 2-5 cumecs. Everything is easy to scout and to portage.

The run starts with some not nice boulder garden rapids. At low flows some of them can be portages.

After that you reach the main part of the run, the bedrock paradise. After few small slides there is a class VI big slide that ends with a slot. Easy portage on the left. After that thre is a serie of very nice slides of different shapes. The granite rock is very smooth and this is what makes this section so famous. Very soon you reach a technical 4-meters drop (class V) with a dangerous cave on the right. Must boof. Few more nice slides bring you to the end of the bedrock section and the start of nasty boulder garden rapids with some minor syphons and undercuts.

At normal flow the grade doesn''t go above IV except for the portage and the 4-meter drop.

**Access**

_Put in:_ Park at the beginning of the dirt road and if the first 100 meters of this road is ok for your car you can drive down. If the water level is low or medium then drive straight at the first intersection and go the point on the map called "Low water put in". By doing this you will avoid lowering you boats down with rope and nasty low water boulder garden paddling.

_Note:_ The run is short but the shuttle is long

