Oitaven is one of the best class IV-V runs in the whole region. It starts from a huge dam and this dam always releases a certain amount of water. The flow doesn''t change naturally. It can stay for days at certain level and then drop significantly within one hour. So just before paddling go online and check the flow and have a backup plan in case of a sudden closure or release of the damn. Usually they will reduce flow if it doesn''t rain and release the water during or just after the rain. It''s unlikely to see an unexpected water release from this damn.

**The run**

With right flow there are no portages and very little flat water. You can start to enjoy Oitaven from 4 cumecs but with this little water you will have to portage few rapids. Around 14 cumecs is probably the ideal flow - no need to portage anything and all the rapids are quite fair. At this flow you will face a very short but must-run class V canyon in the beginning. With much more water this part would probably become too dangerous that''s why we have defined 16 cumecs as the upper limit.

After this short canyon everything is scoutable and portageable and the eddies between the rapids are mostly big enough. The further you paddle the cleaner river becomes and at some point you will start enjoying bedrock rapids. The crux rapid in this part is a long slide with a big but manageable hole at the end. Few more nice slides bring you to a spectacular and clean double drop

After this drop the rapids become easier and very soon all the fun is over.

If there is too much water you can paddle just the part after the drop. There is a dirt road to the river but it''s not easy to find.

