The run takes at least 8 hours if you don''t stop for a rest and don''t have any issues. Plan spending 10-12 hours on this section. So yes, it''s a multiday.

There are up to 100 awesome slides, technical drops, some slots and a lot of nasty boulder gardens to portage.

**Water**

It''s very hard to find a proper flow in this river. If it looks like 10 cumecs - it''s way too much. If it''s around 2 cumecs then the river is more like some grade IV-V slides with a lot, a lot of portages and nasty syphony boulder gardens. 3-5 cumecs is probably the level when you can enjoy the river the most. If the rapid above the put in bridge looks nice with enough water to be really fun to paddle then it''s too high. If it''s not passable then it''s too low. Keep in mind that the flow rises and drops very fast and you paddle this river very slow. Don''t put in if the water level feels alright but it''s raining really hard.

The last gorge would be perfect with 4-7 cumecs but well.. You have to get there somehow.

**Multiday vs a day run**

There is no road or path following the river. And there are more than 10 portages. Doing them with a multiday gear would be a nightmare. Maybe the best advise is to leave empty boats after the first day and hike out and then come back next morning. Where to hike out? Well, there is no good advise for that. There is a path on the top of the hill on the right bank which leads back to the put in bridge or to the village of Vitoreira. It''s around 15 minutes to get to the bridge from the power tower on the top of that hill. Use google satellite and download the images to your phone before putting in. Take this description with you as well.

As far as I know almost everybody who tried to paddle this section in 1 day ended up in darkness. It''s doable - just start paddling at 8:00 but not at 10:00 and be really fit.

**The run**

The first kilometer is really nice. Fair slides and small drops with big enough pools in between. Then you reach the first portage - a 3 meter drop landing on the rock. The next slide with a slot at the end can be paddled or the slot can be portaged on the right if the water is not too high to catch the right eddie before the slot. The following section should be portaged on the right. The local paddlers were so kind to put a good bolt there for rappelling.

There is a nice 3 meter boof just after you finish the portage. Then there is a small double drop and a nice sequence of slides. Be carefull to stop before the 8 meters waterfall that starts with a slide and lands too close to the rock. It''s easy to portage and also it is probably the best spot to hike out from the valley to the right.

The river keeps on going very steep... At some point bedrock character changes to boulder garden and you just start to portage everything swearing the river... But then once again zere narrows and some nice section follow. In general you need more water for the last third of the run. If you made it down to here at high flow than the fun just goes on! Just at the end there is a triple drop which is hard to portage but it''s ok to paddle. Don''t give up here! It''s just 5 minutes to the take out bridge.

**_Note 1:_** There are a lot of thorns and very sharp nasty plants. Be ready to damage your drysuits if you scout and portage a lot and if you need to hike out.

**_Note 2_**: I stopped counting portages on number 10

**_Note 3:_** If the water is too high you can paddle the part from the take out bridge to the confluence with river Vez

