Skjoli is a glacier fed river. The warmer night is the more water you will have! And of course you can experience significant water rise in the afternoon on hot summer days. Skjoli is unlikely to have a lot of water during the spring snowmelt - it''s too cold for it.

Don''t just put in without knowing the exact water level! You can check the gauge at the take out or you can ask or check it in the [facebook group](https://www.facebook.com/groups/1605517383052733). Under 1.45 the river is more like bony class IV. The optimum level is between 1.45 to 1.55. From 1.55 the river becomes a solid class V. The pool with the gauge starts to boil more and it''s hard to say if it''s 1.6 or 1.65 at the moment. Above 1.7 it''s a real commitment without any chance for mistake.

**The run**

The rapid under the bridge at the put in is the steepest and the hardest one. The rest of the river downstream is formed but relatively small boulders which tend to move slightly after the floods. The rapids change a little bit every year so if it''s your first time ever or this year take it easy and scout all steeper parts. You might also find new trees in the river.

This section is really continuous and you will never haver a rest. When the walls of the gorge start to become more vertical the difficulty of the rapids is actually going down. The river remains very continuous though.

In 2015 a long race was held on the whole section. Some paddlers use this section for lapsing and keeping up the paddling shape.

**The scenary**

The valey is very spectacular and very cold. You will probably not notice anything during your run except how cold is the water so enjoy it before! The put in is the start for many beautiful hikes to the glacier.

**Access:**

_Put in:_ End of the dirt road. This is a toll road (70 NOK). Follow the signes to Lundalen.

_Take out:_ On the way to the put in stop on the road close to the last house on the left. Find a path to the river. It will bring you to a low canyon with the gauge. Check the gauge before puting on the river! The river will always seem small and funny here - don''t be fooled and trust the gauge :)

You can also paddle class III+ for 10 minutes down to the road bridge or a bit further to the Skjak kayak camping (Storoya camping) after the confluence with Otta.

