**Water**

It''s a steep river without a dam and it starts at a big plateau. It stays with enough water for paddling for more than 8 days after the rainfall. Very often there are small local rains or some snowmelt in Peneda mountains. Due to these facts you can head to Castro Laboreiro when everything else is low. On the other side it''s almost the only river in the region that has too much water quite often in winter. So don''t come here when other rivers have a lot of water.

There is a gauge at the put in bridge. Low ater is 2.0 and high water is 2.35. There are also green and red marks. The water should be between two green ones. 2.4 is paddleable but it''s very demanding without knowing the river.

**The run**

Everything is possible to scout and to portage

It starts from the take out of the upper section with exactly the same style - nasty class IV- boulder garden with syphons at low flow and nice class IV continuous rapids at high flow.

Just before the waterfalls there are two harder class IV-V rapids.

The first 6-7 meter waterfall can be scouted from the left or right just from the edge.

The second 9-10 meter waterfall can be scouted from the left just from the edge. Usually they scout the 2nd and the 3rd together but it''s actually possible to get out both on the left and right banks after the 2nd one if you have good shoes and not too high flow.

The third 9-12 meter waterfall has a scary cave on the right and a lot of people were washed in there but then flushed away quite soon inside the boats and outside.

Then the long portage follows. Climb up to the view point then follow the hiking path and go down at it''s lowest point. Alternatively you can rapell down on the left bank just after the third waterfall using the anchor and some gear left there by locals. Then you can also run or portage the following drops.

After the portage there are the same style rapids as before the waterfalls with an exception of one slide with a powerfull towback at medium-high flows.

The take out is 200 meters after the foot bridge. But don''t be afraid to miss it - you will never miss the artificial Lindoso lake.

**Access** 

Both roads to the put in and take out are good but driving from the put in to the take out takes around 1 hour.

_Put in:_ Leave your car at the last loop of the serpantine.

If you have only one car the best idea is just to follow the hiking path on the left bank from the take out to the put in. It will take you around 1 hour.

