The water is diverted by the dam for the whole run. The dam is 1 km after the put in and it takes roughly 20 cumecs but they can suddenly close it or open while you are running the river. The optimum amount is around 15-25 cumecs after the dam. Above 30 the section becomes much more demanding. Don''t go into the gorge if it feels like more than 30 cumecs after the dam and it''s your first time on the river.

You can get an idea about the water level at the put in bridge and ask locals there. Average or slightly above average should be good but you will never know exactly before you reach the dam.

When the area is high the dam can actually help you - otherwise the gorge of Calderas would be too high.

**The run**

It''s hands down 5 stars run. The section consists of endless technical drops not all of them are fair. It''s kind of a boulder garden pool-drop style. 

The crux part is quite long, very steep and require a lot of scouting. Horizon lines makes you feel like a portage is coming but as soon as you start scouting you find out that there are always cleen and fun lines! Still probably you will be happy to portage some drops. Everything is scoutable and portagable.

The dam in the beginning is also runnable and the pool after it is deep enough. You can scout it from the right using a small underwater step just at the edge.

It''s defenitely worth to paddle it again and then one more time and then again! The first time it will take you the whole day but then you can do it within 1 hour.

**Access**

The put in is on the main highway. The road to the take out is new and good. It''s a dirt road but doable with no problems with a normal car or van. Take out on the left bank just after the water release from the power station and use a small path to go up.

Alternatively you can paddle for 2 hours class III-IV with a lot of flats all the way down to the Samana bridge.

_Note:_ The resolution of sattelite images from google for this section are excellent!

