**About the river**

Suarez is probably the most famous white water river in Colombia. It''s paddled quite often although the river is very demanding and most of the parts are class V. It''s world famous for being "class V big-volume multiday". The normal approach to this river is doing a 4-5 days multiday trip from Barbosa to the confluence with Chicamocha. But some folks prefer to paddle empty boats because of the difficulty of the river. Also different parts are good at different water levels. There are some easy and medium-easy approaches to the river at some places between Barbosa and the commercial section. So in this description we will divide the run into few parts.

**Water**

There is a gauge at the put in of rafting section. You can check it out or call to Exploradores Colombia. +57 304 670 0025 (what''s app).

This section can be paddled at pretty much any water level but at some levels it gets really big and scary. 5.0 at the gauge is basically flood but it''s still runnable and there are not too many holes left so probably it''s possible with even more.

**The run**

The river changes it''s style again. Instead of long wide rapids with a lot of rocks you will find low but box canyons and pure big volume style.

Everything is portageable and scoutable unless you didn''t bother taking an eddy before entering one of the canyons.

On the first kilometers of the run the river narrows and steep rapids start. There are 6 very steep and powerful rapids with not really big eddies in between.

Then around 30 minutes of flat water and then river enters a box but low canyon. There is a path on the left - you can scout all the canyon but it''s hard to see the river because of very dense vegetation.

Then the river opens up but the rapids continue and they are still class V.

After couple few more long rapids in gorges (not really box) you finally reach the take out bridge.

The section takes the whole day to paddle.

If you liked it - repeat it! You don''t even need a 4-wheel drive to paddle this one!

