## ENGLISH

Yazgulem is a steep glacier river running through canyons and sometimes open steep parts. It is born on the Southern side of the famous Fedchenko glacier. This section can be paddled without portages but all the rapids tend to change quite often.

**Water level**

The perfect water level for this section is 20-40 cumecs in the beginning. With less water it''s probably too bony and with more water the river will become a solid class V-V+.

The hardest sections are easy to scout and to portage. There are some class IV must-runs in canyons.

**The run**

From the start there is nice and continues but not too fast class IV- paddling. The banks become steeper and the river enters the first gorge. If the beginning is demanding for you then don''t paddle further!

Just after one of the 90 left bends Yazgulem rushes down with a long steep class V rapid. Scout and portage if needed from the left.

The following box canyon is easier (class IV) and you can paddle it in eddy-hoping style.

Then the river flattens for a while and you reach a road bridge. But there is still a lot of sweet whitewater left!

Soon you reach another canyon with class IV+ rapids in it.

After the canyon the style of the river changes. It becomes wider and more open and the gradient becomes more constant. There are hundreds of waves and holes and dozens lines between them!

In a small canyon that follows there is a huge rock island in the river just before the right bend. There is a bridge just after this rock. This place is better to scout beforehand because of an unfinished dam just under the bridge. This dam can be run at certain conditions but the syphons around are really dangerous.

Don''t take out here! There is still lot of fun fast water class IV (IV+) paddling after the dam before the river flattens completely and you reach the take out bridge.

Note 1: Don''t paddle to the Pyang river if you are not looking for troubles with boarder forces of both Tadjikistan and Afghanistan.

Note 2: The local people are different from other people of Tadjikistan. They are the same or even more friendly and hospital. Join them for a cup of tea!

