**Water level**

The river is small. It''s easy to get an idea of the water level at the put in drops. If the second one looks like fun - go for it! This section needs a bit less water than the very upper one

**The run**

Just after the put in there are two drops. They are actually a tourist attraction. Both of them are runnable but the first one is very bony. After the drops the run goes on in a beautiful wild surrounding with some class IV rapids.

**Access**

The _put in_ is a foot bridge just by the road.

You can _take out_ at the bridge of O Casal or paddle few easy rapids to the beginning of the gorge. On the entrance to the gorge there are some really beautiful and technical class IV and class V drops but if you paddle them you''ll need to be prepared to find you way out of the gorge before it rushes down with waterfalls in a box canyon. This canyon has to be discovered and probably it''s only a canyoning but not a kayaking adventure.

_Mike Krutyansky, 2018_', 'Just after rain', '4-12 cumecs', '2018-03-24 15:12:52.10677+00', '2018-03-24 15:12:52.10677+00');

**Water level**

min: 95cm mid:120cm max:145cm

If you know the river or you are familiar with big volume it should be no problem to run her with more than max until 170cm. If it gets higher than 170cm you should be very careful because she gets extremely fast and a swim could end up in a disaster.

The river drains 2 lakes, so during snow melt or after heavy rains it keeps water for some days up to weeks.

[Online Gauge](http://hydro.ooe.gv.at/#4030)

There is an answering machine that tells you the water level in real time (austrian):

+436131606

**The run**

There is a trail up from the take out next to the river, so everything can be scouted and portaged on riverbank left. The run starts rather easy for about 2km. After the third bridge of the railway things become more serious and you will get first impressions of what will be ahead. You will see and hear the first rapid and there is time to stop and scout on river left. The entry drop can be boofed to the eddy on river left and then follow the left line to middle or again to left. (At higher levels 135cm+ there is a nice autoboof at the exit over a big rock into a large pool). The right line of the rapid is less demanding. Shortly after the large pool starts the second rapid. You should scout it on river left. Its much longer, more technical and demanding than the first rapid. In the middle of the rapid is a big hole you should take care of and paddle hard to the right. Swimming here is not a good idea. After the second rapid the river is continuous class IV with big waves and holes almost until 1 km before the take out when she finally calms down.

_Tip_: Take the train for a second run or the shuttle, directly from take out (Obertraun) to put in (Bad Aussee, 1 station), goes every 2 hours, 2,60 per Person

_Daniel Fast, 2018_

_Accomodation:_

[Official camping](http://www.camping-am-see.at): Winkl 77, 4831 Obertraun

Hostels apartments: Obertraun in the village

